		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message30542079">I think it can be, but having style won't necessarily create substance. For example, Kill la Kill is all style,  no substance. And even though many of the characters wouldn't stand out, or might even be completely irrelevant in a show with generic animation, much of the supporting cast is quite popular, such as MC's best friend (whose name I forget). I think that's a great example of style creating substance. The unique presentation allows viewers to see her for more than he interactions and character development made her out to be. Only in this unique setting would she have excelled as a character. <br />
<br />
There would likewise be examples to the contrary. For example, Wolf's Rain was praised for its detailed and quality animation, but it still manages to have plenty of flat, boring, or uninspired supporting (and also main) characters.</div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig"><span style="font-size: 80%;"><div style="text-align: center;"><img class="userimg" data-src="http://fc06.deviantart.net/fs42/f/2009/096/7/8/Tonberry_Banner_by_Doaj.jpg" /><br />
