		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message30542717">I'll hopefully add more to this topic later, but I'm curious why "style" can't exist on its own, and become the show's main "substance" (substance is such a stupid word). Like, can't something just strive to be pretty? I mean, it works for paintings. Does making them motherfuckers move suddenly place all these bizarre constrictions on what they can and should be? Of course, if there's an attempt at an actual story that gets in the way of this and falls short in its own ways, yeah, that's an issue. But how about the other cases? Stuff like Dead Leaves or Redline that aim for style, spectacle, and nothing more. Sure, you can say their stories are implausible or that the guy with a TV for a head didn't receive meaningful development, but that's missing the point of them entirely. They are their style; that is their substance. They're beautiful!<br />
<br />
Delicacies of Molten Horror Synapse is my favorite anime: <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UBjuDWNPeno" target="_blank"><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UBjuDWNPeno" target="_blank">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UBjuDWNPeno</a></a></div><div style="margin-top: 8px;"><em>Modified by RMNDolphy, 05-05-14, 1:16 AM</em></div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig"><div style="text-align: right;"><!--link--><a href="http://drillmilkyholmes.wordpress.com/" rel="nofollow"><img src="http://i.imgur.com/7ALjX4f.png" /></a></div></td>
