		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message30572197"><!--quote--><div class="quotetext"><strong>Nagisa33 said:</strong><!--quotesaid--><br>A cake can look pretty but it also has to taste good.<!--quote--></div><br />
<br />
Some cakes are intended only as visual displays.  Is that an inherently bad thing?<br />
<br />
I think the discussion of "all style, no substance" is one worth having.  There are definite anime that function solely on the basis of style.  To be clear, I'm not talking about stuff like many of the examples mentioned here.  Yeah, a big part of a show like Baccano or Bakemonogatari is style, but it's not all style with zero substance--the fact that these works existed in light novel form prior to being adapted to anime form is pretty clear evidence of that.  Strip the "style" out of something like JJBA and you still have a story about a 20th century Englishman fighting vampires or chasing after Mexican artifacts.<br />
<br />
Koji Morimoto's music video shorts are interesting exercises because they are adaptive in a certain sense, but instead of working around the source material of a light novel, they are built around a piece of music.  For a really solid example of this, see Extra: <!--link--><a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=t6maVVFs0As" rel="nofollow"><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=t6maVVFs0As" target="_blank">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=t6maVVFs0As</a></a><br />
<br />
The music is without lyric or theme, so in terms of "substance," the task for the animators is to literally create something from nothing, manufacturing a functional production where their only contribution is visual style.</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
