		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message30687149">Going along with the cake analogy: You guys haven't tried cakes composed entirely of icings before? What a shame. They're tasty, but aren't fit for <em>uncultured</em> gentlemen I suppose.<br />
<br />
Style is another way of conveying something through the means of creativity. In other words, it is oftentimes taking what is cliched and revamping it anew. Sometimes it works; other times its disastrous. <br />
<br />
For instance, TTGL is hella good because it promotes morale in a refreshing way: (manly) screams after manly screams, in its animated form, actually felt palpable enough to generate a resonating, homely feeling. Then, there's stuff like Angel's Egg, School Days, or Millennium Bullshit that try too hard to be different that the deliverance, execution, and so on and so forth wound up as overly heavy-handed and pretentious. A more recent example would be Kill la kill, whose first arc is actually no style and no substance plastered in slight Gainax flavor. By this, I mean that using the "monster/battle of the week" formula as a way to introduce characters is hardly new, and is severely distasteful. But again, Gainax-rebels/Trigger does put its own spin on it. So its kinda okay I guess, but that's a conversation for another time.<br />
<br />
Stylized substance is almost always good. Just don't get consumed by it, as with all things in life. Well, unless its healthy and has very little repercussions (like eating and exercising, but even then one has to recover); then by all means, consume away.</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
